{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e58aea9-3fa0-4b02-aed0-66257d05f1f7","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest way to collect a CPU profile for .NET apps.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper analysis, ETW events, GC/threading issues |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check (`cpu-usage`, `threadpool-queue-length`) before tracing |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | OS-level + .NET combined traces |\n\n### Pro tip — quick triage first:\n```powershell\n# See live counters before committing to a full trace\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis tells you instantly if it's GC pressure, thread starvation, or pure CPU work — then you can target your trace accordingly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82f73198-073d-4d79-b023-1f6201156061","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on diagnosing a CPU issue with a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I should give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":397},"id":"3679942e-ad42-4077-84d2-1e5139a9026f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:48:56.634Z","parentId":"60c8cdc6-f5cc-4717-aece-9ff6aaff55b8"}
